The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Business Briefs

 New Delhi, Feb. 19: The Telecom Regulatory Authority of India will meet tomorrow to give final touches to the new access deficit charge (ADC) regime, sources said. The ADC quantum paid to BSNL may come down to Rs 3,143 crore annually from the current Rs 5,340 crore, they added. The telecom tariff, especially the STD call rates, are likely to fall significantly with Trai proposing to reduce the levy paid by private operators to BSNL by over Rs 1,900 crore.

 New Delhi, Feb. 19: The board of the Airports Authority of India (AAI) will meet tomorrow to finalise the minute details of restructuring Delhi and Mumbai airports before handing over them to private parties by March 31. It is a part of the series of meetings being conducted by the board.

 Barcelona, Feb. 19: Identifying India as its major market, Motorola has sought suitable tax policies for the telecom sector, like duty cut on mobile devices, from the government.

 Mumbai, Feb. 19: The Tata-controlled Videsh Sanchar Nigam Ltd, along with Tata Consultancy Services and Tata Teleservices, will tap the global market jointly. ?It will be a purely business-to-business relationship,? said TCS chief executive and managing director S. Ramadorai.

 Bangkok, Feb. 19: Max New York Life has sought changes in tax laws, especially the fringe benefit and services tax, and more incentives for the country?s booming insurance sector in the budget for 2006-07.




